<BIOGRAPHY SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Winifred Maxwell, Countess of Nithsdale: biography</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Created from original research by members of the Orlando Project</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>21 October 2011</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>1 November 2011</DATE></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>3 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>9 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>18 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>18 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>23 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>23 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv p</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>24 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>28 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>30 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>14 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb, cft c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Biography</HEADING><STANDARD>Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of</STANDARD><DIV1><PERSONNAME><DIV2><DATASTRUCT><DATAITEM><BIRTHNAME REG="Herbert, Lady Winifred"><GIVEN>Winifred</GIVEN><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Scholar <NAME>Henrietta Tayler</NAME> spells her name Winfrede, and <NAME STANDARD="Durrant, Catherine S.">Catherine S. Durrant</NAME> spells it Winefred. But others agree on Winifred.</P></SCHOLARNOTE><SURNAME>Herbert</SURNAME></BIRTHNAME> </DATAITEM><DATAITEM><STYLED REG="Herbert, Lady Winifred">Lady</STYLED></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><MARRIED WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Maxwell</MARRIED></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><TITLED WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Countess of Nithsdale</TITLED></DATAITEM></DATASTRUCT></DIV2></PERSONNAME></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Birth and Family</HEADING><BIRTH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE>1672</DATE><CHRONPROSE><BIRTHPOSITION POSITION="YOUNGEST"><NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Lady Winifred Herbert (later Nithsdale)</NAME> was born, the last of a family of six children, all girls except one.</BIRTHPOSITION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></BIRTH></DIV1><DIV1><CULTURALFORMATION><CLASSISSUE><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>She came from an <CLASS SOCIALRANK="NOBILITY" SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">ancient, noble</CLASS>, <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church"><DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Roman Catholic">Roman Catholic</DENOMINATION></ORGNAME> family, who were <NATIONALITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="English">English</NATIONALITY> with some claim to be <NATIONALITY REG="Welsh">Welsh</NATIONALITY>. <NAME>Sheffield Grace</NAME>, who wrote comments on her famous letter in 1827, ascribed her qualities to her descent: he felt that she was of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">superior clay</QUOTE> and that her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">virtues</QUOTE> (which later generations would see as heroism, a combination of courage, decisiveness, and executive ability) <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">were probably owing to the mould of true mental nobility in which they were cast by the example and precepts of her illustrious progenitors.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Nithsdale, Letter 1827, 10" DBREF="70107">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Winifred took her religion seriously, and made a retreat in a convent at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Pontoise</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> before her wedding.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 26" DBREF="70285">26</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell and William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell and William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></CLASSISSUE></CULTURALFORMATION></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="MOTHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Mother</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Lady Winifred&apos;s mother, <NAME STANDARD="Powis, Elizabeth Herbert,,, Duchess of">Elizabeth Herbert, Baroness and eventually Duchess of Powis</NAME>, came from an influential <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholic</ORGNAME> royalist family. One of her great-grand-mothers was the Renaissance translator <NAME STANDARD="Russell, Elizabeth,,, Lady">Elizabeth Russell</NAME> (one of the famous Cook sisters). She herself was an active Catholic, even a Catholic <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="political activist">activist</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> in conjunction with the midwife-writer <NAME>Elizabeth Cellier</NAME>. Lady Powis (as she then was) was accused of treasonous plotting in the so-called and largely fictitious <SOCALLED>Meal Tub Plot</SOCALLED> (about which she <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="writer">composed and had printed at least one and probably two ballads</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>). She was a prisoner in the <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Tower of London">Tower of London</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> from <DATERANGE FROM="1679-11-04" TO="1680-02-12" EXACT="BOTH">4 November 1679 to 12 February 1680</DATERANGE>, her shorter period of incarceration overlapping with her husband&apos;s longer one.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268">under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>When the English court turned Catholic, Lady Powis served as <JOB REG="courtier">lady-in-waiting</JOB> to the queen, <NAME STANDARD="Mary of Modena,, Queen of England">Mary of Modena</NAME>. She was a witness to the birth of the king and queen&apos;s baby <NAME STANDARD="Stuart, James Edward">son</NAME>, was appointed his <SOCALLED>governess</SOCALLED> (a <JOB REG="governess">post</JOB> she retained for the rest of her life), and helped him to survive the dubious childcare practices of the time. With her husband and the royal family she left England for exile abroad, and she died on <DATE>11 March 1691</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268">under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Tayler 7-8" DBREF="70086">7-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="FATHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Father</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Winifred&apos;s father, <NAME STANDARD="Powis, William Herbert,,, first Duke of">William Herbert</NAME>, was a major <JOB REG="land-owner">land-owner</JOB> in the Welsh marches and Wales proper, a convinced and hereditary monarchist, as <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="politician">active in government</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> as his <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholic</ORGNAME> religion allowed, a <JOB>courtier</JOB> and a <JOB REG="army officer">soldier</JOB>. He suffered arrest and imprisonment at the time of the national hysteria over <NAME>Titus Oates</NAME>&apos;s alleged <SOCALLED>Popish Plot</SOCALLED>. He spent five and a half years in the <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Tower of London">Tower</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, and whereas his wife published ballads about the various plots he <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="writer">published a pamphlet</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>. Under <NAME STANDARD="James II, King">James II</NAME> he rose by gradual steps to a dukedom, and he became a moderating voice in the king&apos;s councils. The exile he shared with the royal family and his own began in December 1688. He died on <DATE>12 July 1696</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268">under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="SISTER"><DIV2><HEADING>Sister</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Among Lady Winifred Herbert&apos;s sisters the closest in age was <NAME STANDARD="Herbert, Lady Lucy">Lady Lucy</NAME>. After the family went into exile in Europe, Lucy became a <JOB>nun</JOB>, then <JOB>prioress</JOB> of the English Augustinians at Bruges, and a published <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="writer">writer</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> of devotional texts.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Growing Up</HEADING><EDUCATION MODE="DOMESTIC"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Since each of Lady Winifred&apos;s parents wrote and published their writing (or allowed it to be published), it seems likely that they valued learning as well as piety in their daughters, but nothing is known of the girls&apos; education. Winifred&apos;s sister Lady Lucy is said to have written about pedagogy in later life, basing her remarks on the practice of experts, which sounds as if she felt she had been well taught.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 430" DBREF="17072">430</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Winifred as a child, like her next elder sister, Lucy, spent most of her early years at the medieval stronghold of <PLACE><PLACENAME>Powis Castle</PLACENAME>, near <SETTLEMENT>Welshpool</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION CURRENT="Powys" REG="Montgomeryshire">Montgomeryshire</REGION><GEOG REG="Wales"></GEOG></PLACE>. After James II came to the throne the family rebuilt and made more use of its grand townhouse in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Lincoln&apos;s Inn Fields</PLACENAME>, <SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 8-9" DBREF="70285">8-9</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268">under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><VIOLENCE><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>These were luxurious but hardly secure places. Powis Castle had been besieged and captured during the English Civil War, and when Winifred was about seven an armed anit-Catholic mob broke into the Lincoln&apos;s Inn Fields house.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268">under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></VIOLENCE></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><HEADING>Exile</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Lady Winifred Herbert (later Lady Nithsdale) joined her parents at the Jacobite court of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="St-Germain-en-Laye">St Germain</SETTLEMENT> in <GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE> only at the end of the autumn in 1691.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 19" DBREF="70285">19</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Winifred succeeded her mother as a <JOB REG="courtier">lady-in-waiting</JOB> to <EMPLOYER><NAME STANDARD="Mary of Modena,, Queen of England">Mary Beatrice of Modena</NAME></EMPLOYER>. While the Jacobite court-in-exile of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="St-Germain-en-Laye">St Germain</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> was where she primarily worked, she became an expert too on the byzantine routine of the French court at Versailles.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 21, 23" DBREF="70285">21, 23</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><WEALTH><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Before he died her <NAME STANDARD="Powis, William Herbert,,, first Duke of">father</NAME> became anxious that Winifred had been treated unfairly in the disposition of family money in comparison with her sisters (three of whom had married while the family was riding high). On his final day alive he re-made his will to leave her the last remaining item of her mother&apos;s jewelry, instead of letting it go, with everything else, to her brother.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 23" DBREF="70285">23</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></WEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Marriage, Children</HEADING><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><MARRIAGE><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE>2 March 1699</DATE><CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Lady Winifred Herbert</NAME> married the Scottish peer <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, William Maxwell,,, fifth Earl of">William Maxwell, Earl of Nithsdale</NAME>, a fellow Catholic and Jacobite, four years younger than she was.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 26" DBREF="70285">26</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></MARRIAGE></MEMBER><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>They had met at the court of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="St-Germain-en-Laye">St Germain</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>. <CHILDREN NUMBER="5">Two children survived from the five born during the marriage (besides others who miscarried), a son called William like his father (born in 1700) and a daughter, Anne (born in 1710), who became by marriage <NAME STANDARD="Bellew, Anne,,, Baroness">Lady Bellew</NAME>.</CHILDREN><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 26, 34-5, 43-4" DBREF="70285">26, 34-5, 43-4</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>With her husband (whose father had died while he was a child) WMCN lived at his family seat, the rugged <PLACE><PLACENAME>Terregles Castle</PLACENAME> near <SETTLEMENT>Dumfries</SETTLEMENT><REGION CURRENT="Dumfries and Galloway" REG="Dumfriesshire"></REGION><RESEARCHNOTE>img to Mariana. Dumfriesshire still exists, though for council purposes it is now part of Dumfries and Galloway. This sounds not too hard to deal with as I have in attributes, but on the other hand Galloway used (before it became part of Dumfries and Galloway) to be an informal region divided for administrative purposes between two counties, Wigtown (or Wigtownshire) and Kirkcudbright. I think all these three forms should remain as Reg attributes where we have them, and Current attribute shd be Dumfries and Galloway. mpo: thanks, added to place cleanup work</RESEARCHNOTE><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE>. She only gradually took over the running of the establishment (which was largely self-sufficient in produce) from her mother-in-law. Life was difficult for them there because the area was largely Presbyterian.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 29-30, 44" DBREF="70285">29-30, 44</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><VIOLENCE><DIV2><HEADING>Difficulties</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE VALUE="1703-12-24">Christmas Eve 1703</DATE><CHRONPROSE>The family home of <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Lady Nithsdale</NAME>, <PLACE><PLACENAME>Terregles Castle</PLACENAME> near <SETTLEMENT>Dumfries</SETTLEMENT><REGION CURRENT="Dumfries and Galloway" REG="Dumfriesshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE>, was broken into by an armed mob a hundred strong, led by Presbyterian ministers, looking for illicit Catholic priests or <ORGNAME REG="Jesuits" STANDARD="Society of Jesus">Jesuits</ORGNAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Catholic priests were banned from Britain; it was assumed that any Jesuit would be spying for a foreign power. Legal proceedings followed against <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, William Maxwell,,, fifth Earl of">William Lord Nithsdale</NAME> for harbouring priests. He was acquitted of the charge, but still penalized: by government surveillance, the loss of an ancient traditional title, and the exaction of money as security for his future conduct. After the abortive Jacobite coup of 1708 he was imprisoned with his brother-in-law <NAME STANDARD="Traquair, Charles Stuart,,, fourth Earl of">Charles, Lord Traquair</NAME>, in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Edinburgh Castle</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Edinburgh"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Midlothian"></REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 40-3" DBREF="70285">40-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></VIOLENCE></DIV1><DIV1><WEALTH><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>A longer-term difficulty in the marriage was Lord Nithsdale&apos;s apparent financial incompetence or total inability to live within his means. He was already besieged by creditors at the time of his marriage, though his bride probably knew nothing of this fact. His estate brought in less than &pound;1,000 a year, and his outgoings were much higher. A few years after his imprisonment at Edinburgh, he made over the estate in trust for his son and agreed to live on an allowance of &pound;500 a year until his debts were paid.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 26-7, 30, 48-9" DBREF="70285">26-7, 30, 48-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></WEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><HEADING>The Jacobite Rebellion of 1715</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, William Maxwell,,, fifth Earl of">Lord Nithsdale</NAME>, husband of WMCN, was at first reluctant to join the badly planned and executed <TOPIC>Jacobite</TOPIC> rebellion of <NAME STANDARD="Mar, John Erskine,,, sixth Earl of">Lord Mar</NAME>, which began when Mar raised his standard on <DATE>6 September 1715</DATE>. In the end, however, Nithsdale joined in. He raised a local force, marched south with the main army, and took part in the battle of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Preston</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lancashire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> on <DATERANGE FROM="1715-11-12" TO="1715-11-13" EXACT="BOTH">12-13 November 1715</DATERANGE>. The battle was lost (on the same day as the more famous and inconclusive battle of Sheriffmuir) and he surrendered immediately afterwards. With a group of other Scots Jacobite lords, he was sent to the <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Tower of London">Tower of London</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, tried for treason, and on 9 February 1716 was sentenced to death by the singularly gruesome method of hanging, drawing, and quartering.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Jacobite activists of the 1715 rising " DBREF="29268">under Jacobite activists of the 1715 rising </BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Her Heroic Exploit</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>The first thing her husband&apos;s arrest meant for Winifred Nithsdale was the need to consult with her relatives at Traquair and to bury in her castle garden valuables including the papers conveying the estate to her son, to keep them out of government hands. The next thing was to travel at the greatest possible speed from <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Terregles Castle">Terregles</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Dumfries"></SETTLEMENT><REGION CURRENT="Galloway and Dumfries" REG="Dumfriesshire"></REGION> in <GEOG REG="Scotland">Scotland</GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> during an exceptionally hard winter. She had with her <NAME>Cecilia Evans</NAME> (a Welsh army officer&apos;s daughter who had been her maid or companion since her youth).<SCHOLARNOTE><P>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> and Flora Stuart Maxwell give her name as Cecilia Evans, while other sources, like <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Welsh Biography Online</TITLE> and a website about the cottage said to have been given her in Welshpool for her retirement, call her <NAME STANDARD="Evans, Cecilia">Grace Evans</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Welsh Biography Online" DBREF="43066"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Lady Nithsdale&apos;s Cottage" DBREF="70105"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 19" DBREF="70285">19</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE> The two women rode on horseback to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Newcastle upon Tyne">Newcastle</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Northumberland"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and thence (there being no seats left on the London coach) onwards to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. There Lady Nithsdale was able to catch a coach, only to have it stick in a snowdrift sixteen miles north of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Grantham</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lincolnshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, forcing her to revert to floundering through the snow on a horse.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 65-6" DBREF="70285">65-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>WMCN had little hope she could secure a pardon for a Catholic rebel, but nevertheless she tried. She drummed up support, appeared regularly in the gallery at the <ORGNAME>House of Lords</ORGNAME>, organized a petition and went to court to present it herself to the king (whom she, like other Jacobites, called <SOCALLED>the Elector</SOCALLED>). When <NAME STANDARD="George I, King">George I</NAME> refused to take the paper; she clutched his robes and held on while he dragged her bodily across the room. This violence on the part of the monarch made a bad impression; Lady Nithsdale became a focus of sympathy and even something of a popular heroine. The petition was in the end read to the king, but it did not have the desired effect.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 232-3" DBREF="19167">2: 232-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>A century later, however, the Rev. <NAME>John Malham</NAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Grand National History of England</TITLE> suggested that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the king or his counsellors probably conclud[ed] that individual mercy may be a public cruelty.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Malham 2: 744" DBREF="70688">2: 744</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><OTHERLIFEEVENT><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="DECADE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE>22 February 1716</DATE><CHRONPROSE>The night before her <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, William Maxwell,,, fifth Earl of">husband</NAME> was due to be executed for treason, <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Winifred, Lady Nithsdale</NAME>, put into effect her daring, risky, but carefully planned scheme for securing his escape from the impregnable <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Tower of London">Tower of London</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifed Maxwell and William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifed Maxwell and William Maxwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She had acquired visiting rights by bribing the guards (avoiding persuasion to stay at the Tower with him, and thus lose her liberty of action). She visited often, and brought friends. On her supposedly final visit she took two supporters (Mrs Mills, her landlady, and Miss or Mrs Hilton, later Morgan) into the Tower, while <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">my deare <NAME STANDARD="Evans, Cecilia">Evans</NAME></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 231" DBREF="19167">2: 231</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> lurked outside. Lady Nithsdale used as a distracting motif the pretence that Evans was expected, but was late. Visitors had to be taken in separately, so the operation proceeded in stages. Hilton, who was slim, wore an extra cloak under her own when she entered, which she left behind before Mills, who was large and pregnant, came in with a handkerchief clutched to her face as if in tears. William Nithsdale found the prospect of being apprehended in women&apos;s clothes almost more repugnant than that of being butchered, so he had to be coaxed and persuaded. Once Mills had left (wearing the extra cloak, no longer crying) and Lady Nithsdale had painted her husband&apos;s face and beard, and got him into all her petticoats but one and into Mills&apos;s cloak, she led him outside while he pretended to weep and she comforted him and complained loudly about Evans. Once he was in his first hiding-place she went back to his cell and stayed for some time, mimicking a two-sided conversation for any listeners. When she did leave she told his manservant (who was not in the secret) that her husband was at prayer and must not be disturbed. Lady Nithsdale went on to make social calls and to enlist the <NAME STANDARD="Montrose, Christian Carnegie Graham,,, Duchess of">Duchess of Montrose</NAME> (the only person at court who was in the secret) to go and watch the king&apos;s reaction to the news of the escape.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 224-9" DBREF="19167">2: 224-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>After she joined her husband outside, the two of them lay for two days in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a poor litle bed</QUOTE> in the house of a poor woman. They had bread and wine but they dared not move in case footsteps were heard and aroused suspicion.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 229" DBREF="19167">2: 229</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OTHERLIFEEVENT></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><HEADING>London, Scotland, Bruges, Rome</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Once she knew her rescued husband had crossed the Channel, Lady Nithsdale set off back from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><GEOG>Scotland</GEOG>, to <PLACENAME REG="Terregles Castle">Terregles</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Dumfries"></SETTLEMENT><REGION CURRENT="Dumfries and Galloway" REG="Dumfriesshire"></REGION></PLACE> for her buried papers. This was dangerous, for she had ascertained that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">in matter of treason . . . a wive&apos;s head answers for her husband&apos;s,</QUOTE> and friends therefore wanted her to go abroad at once, but she needed to secure the legal documents for her son&apos;s inheritance.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 232" DBREF="19167">2: 232</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She travelled like a fugitive, with <NAME STANDARD="Evans, Cecilia">Evans</NAME> and a trusted Scottish servant, staying in poor, out-of-the-way inns instead of anywhere she might be known. At home she told the neighbours she was there by permission, and proceeded to strip the house (now forfeit to the government) in order to sell what she could and store the rest. She also dug up the estate papers (preserved by the cold) and sent them for safe keeping to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Innerleithen"></SETTLEMENT><PLACENAME>Traquair House</PLACENAME><REGION CURRENT="Borders" REG="Peeblesshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE>. After another surreptitious journey south, and after consulting a lawyer about her prospects, she realised she must go abroad to be safe. She then sailed on a ship which was forced to put her ashore at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Helvoetsluys</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Netherlands"></GEOG></PLACE> because she was so seasick that she miscarried.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 92" DBREF="70285">92</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell 312" DBREF="70088">312</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 232" DBREF="19167">2: 232</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She reached <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bruges</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Belgium" REG="Belgium"></GEOG></PLACE> on <DATE VALUE="1716-08-12">12 August</DATE> (with her little daughter, plus Evans and another attendant), and stayed there for a month before meeting her husband at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Lille</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> in <DATE>September 1716</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 94-6" DBREF="70285">94-6</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McArthur 117" DBREF="70125">117</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 323-4" DBREF="17072">323-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>On arriving in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> in January-February 1716 Winifred Nithsdale was ill, but she did not let her physical condition interfere with her campaign.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 217" DBREF="19167">2: 217</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 70" DBREF="70285">70</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH><HEALTH ISSUE="FEMALEBODY"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>This was probably too early to have been connected with the pregnancy which she mentioned in late May, facing the ride back south from <PLACE><GEOG>Scotland</GEOG> (<PLACENAME REG="Terregles Castle">Terregles</PLACENAME>)<SETTLEMENT REG="Dumfries"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Dumfriesshire"></REGION></PLACE>. She then wanted if possible to sit pillion behind another rider: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">for I am affraid almost of rideing single for fear of the pomell, I am grown so big.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell 312" DBREF="70088" QTDIN="QTDINYES">312</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In July, however, she suffered a dangerous miscarriage during a storm at sea. The foetus which had survived so many hours of hard riding succumbed to its mother&apos;s fearful seasickness after her ship put out from England for the Continent. Even after a month&apos;s recuperation in the care of her sister, WMCN relapsed again after travelling south to join her husband.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 241, 247" DBREF="19167">2: 241, 247</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell 312" DBREF="70088">312</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 94-7" DBREF="70285">94-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Life in Exile</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Lord Nithsdale had left the Jacobite court-in-exile (then at Avignon) to join his wife at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Lille</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, and incurred displeasure for doing so. For some time the question of where to live was hard to resolve. WMCN visited <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="St-Germain-en-Laye">St Germain</SETTLEMENT> in <GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE> to try to secure court employment, but was unsuccessful. She stayed a year or more in <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG>, living at <SETTLEMENT>La Fl&egrave;che</SETTLEMENT></PLACE>, attending to her children&apos;s education and keeping an ear to the ground for possible employment.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 97, 105-6" DBREF="70285">97, 105-6</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><HEADING>Finishing the Journey</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>In the summer of 1718, after the death of Mary of Modena and after a prolonged struggle raising money to travel, WMCN set out with Evans to travel from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, or rather to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Urbino</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, whence the Jacobite court was about to move to Rome itself. They travelled via <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Lyons</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, the <PLACE><REGION>Mont Cenis</REGION> Pass<GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Turin</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bologna</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 109-11, 113-14" DBREF="70285">109-11, 113-14</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE>October 1718</DATE><CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Lady Nithsdale</NAME> arrived, after nearly two months&apos; travelling from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, at the Jacobite court at  <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Urbino</SETTLEMENT> in <GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>, arriving in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">nearly rags</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 127" DBREF="70285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">127</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> for her first court appearance. </CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 113-14" DBREF="70285">113-14</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She reached Urbino only to find herself in straits for money for an imminent move, with the rest of the court, to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 113-14" DBREF="70285">113-14</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>She was ill again in February 1919.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 288" DBREF="19167">2: 288</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><HEADING>Court Life</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Mary of Modena,, Queen of England">Mary of Modena</NAME> had no position to give, though she wrote a letter of advice. Lady Nithsdale offered her services to a potential wife of <NAME STANDARD="Stuart, James Edward">James Edward</NAME> as soon as the existence of such a person was mooted. Since James was in Spain when his bride, <EMPLOYER><NAME>Clementina Sobieska</NAME></EMPLOYER>, arrived in Rome, Nithsdale met her before he did. By <DATE VALUE="1719-05-" CERTAINTY="BY">May 1719</DATE> she was a <JOB REG="courtier">member of Clementina&apos;s household</JOB>, though the post was a mixed blessing because of the bitter infighting that characterised the Jacobite court. Furthermore, she was passed over for a position caring for Charles Edward, the elder son of James and Clementina. This was a hierarchical society traditionally based on patronage and display: since those at the top had little or nothing to offer, and their supporters could not afford to do anything in the grand manner, neither public nor private relations functioned normally.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 252, 259, 294" DBREF="19167">2: 252, 259, 294</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 106-7, 120, 126-7" DBREF="70285">106-7, 120, 126-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Winifred Nithsdale did, however, eventually follow in the footsteps of her mother in serving as a <JOB REG="governess">royal governess</JOB> in the exiled Stuart family: in her case to <NAME>Henry Benedict Stuart</NAME> (Charles Edward&apos;s younger brother, who became eventually a Roman Catholic cardinal). She filled this role in practice from the time when he was a baby, but it was not until <DATE>4 July 1727</DATE>, when <SOCALLED>James III</SOCALLED> was planning to leave for Spain for a possible invasion of Britain after the death of George I, that a pompous document officially inaugurated <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Our Right Trusty and Right well beloved Winifred Countess of Nithsdale into the place and quality of governess to our dearly beloved son Henry Duke of York.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 140, 143" DBREF="70285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">140, 143</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The appointment lasted only until the little boy was four, when he was reckoned of an age to have male teachers. Winifred Nithsdale remained with Clementina Sobieska until the latter&apos;s early death in 1735.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 149, 153" DBREF="70285">149, 153</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><HEADING>Rome and Bologna</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Lady Nithsdale and her husband took rooms near the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Muti Palace</PLACENAME> in <SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> , where the Jacobite court was lodged. To economise they shared a cook with others in the same building.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 115" DBREF="70285">115</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> From autumn 1726 WMCN spent some time, without her husband, in attendance on the two sons of <SOCALLED>James III</SOCALLED>, first at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bologna</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG> and then at the nearby <PLACENAME>Villa Almandine</PLACENAME></PLACE>, where James hoped that Clementina, who had made a political withdrawal to a convent, might rejoin them, as she did the following year. Clementina&apos;s court, and WMCN with it, moved back to Rome in June 1728.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 140-2, 144, 149" DBREF="70285">140-2, 144, 149</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell and James Francis Edward" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell and James Francis Edward</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><HEADING>Relations and Friends</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>WMCN&apos;s early and close relationship with her sister-in-law <NAME STANDARD="Traquair, Mary Stewart,,, Countess of (wife of the fourth Earl)">Mary, Countess of Traquair</NAME>, <FOREIGN REG="born" LANG="fr">n&eacute;e</FOREIGN> Maxwell, suffered vicissitudes over the years through her poverty and her husband&apos;s shameless requests for money. In 1718 the Traquairs became restive over the Nithsdales&apos; constant need for financial help, and Mary Traquair was upset by minor criticisms of her spendthrift brother by his wife. Later, a yet more flagrant injustice by William Nithsdale made her understand her sister-in-law&apos;s point of view. In Rome Lady Nithsdale formed a friendship with <NAME STANDARD="Mar, Frances Erskine,,, Countess of">Lady Mar</NAME> (sister of <NAME>Lady Mary Wortley Montagu</NAME> and wife of the Jacobite leader Lord Mar).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 109-11, 118, 126-7, 135" DBREF="70285">109-11, 118, 126-7, 135</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The letter-writer <NAME STANDARD="Pomfret, Henrietta Louisa Fermor,,, Countess of">Lady Pomfret</NAME> met Lady Nithsdale in Rome in 1741 and found her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">now grown very old.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Hertford-Pomfret Correspondence 3: 55, 65" DBREF="50845">3: 55, 65</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>When this letter was printed in 1805 the editor inserted a misleading footnote ascribing the rescue to Lord Nithsdale&apos;s mother, not his wife. This version was followed by historian <NAME STANDARD="Malham, John">John Malham</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Malham 2: 745" DBREF="70688">2: 745</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="DAUGHTER"><DIV2><HEADING>Later Family Life</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>The Nithsdales&apos; daughter <NAME STANDARD="Bellew, Anne,,, Baroness">Anne</NAME>, having been left behind in Paris in 1718 for education at a convent, rejoined her parents in Italy only in 1729. There she married a Protestant, John, Lord Bellew, in the same year that her brother married Catherine Stuart, one of his Traquair cousins. In 1735 the Bellews returned to London, and there Anne died soon after the birth of her second child. The little boy died too, and his elder sister, Frances, was sent back to her grandmother&apos;s care, though her father provided for her support.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 109, 111, 149-51, 153-5" DBREF="70285">109, 111, 149-51, 153-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, William Maxwell,,, fifth Earl of">William Nithsdale</NAME>&apos;s financial troubles became ever more desperate as the years went by. He touched his wife&apos;s friends for money behind her back, sent begging letters which still survive, and when he had cash let it run through his fingers unaccounted for and without mentioning it to her. By 1722 she was trying to keep her own finances apart from his.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fraser 2: 274, 277, 302-3, 332, 342-3" DBREF="19167">2: 274, 277, 302-3, 332, 342-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><WEALTH><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Winifred Nithsdale spent her first years abroad living on a Jacobite pension, which was augmented by <NAME STANDARD="Mary of Modena,, Queen of England">Mary Beatrice of Modena</NAME> until the latter&apos;s death on <DATE>7 May 1718</DATE>. After years of hand-to-mouth existence, she received in her widowhood an annuity of two hundred pounds a year from her son. She paid all her husband&apos;s debts before she died.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 106, 109" DBREF="70285">106, 109</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell and Mary of Modena" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell and Mary of Modena</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Tayler xi" DBREF="70086">xi</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></WEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Deaths of her Husband and Herself</HEADING><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE>20 March 1744</DATE><CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, William Maxwell,,, fifth Earl of">William, Lord Nithsdale</NAME> (husband of WMCN), died in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under William Maxwell</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Tayler 244" DBREF="70086">244</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><DEATH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE>May 1749</DATE><CHRONPROSE>WMCN died in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> after five years of widowhood.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268">under Winifred Maxwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></DEATH></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Durrant, Catherine S. Flemish Martyrs.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Maxwell, Sir Herbert. A History of Dumfries and Galloway. 2nd ed. 1900</SOURCE><SOURCE>Maxwell Taylor, Flora. Lady Nithsdale and the Jacobites. 1995.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Taylor, Henrietta. The Jacobite Court. 1938. 70085</SOURCE><SOURCE>Tayler, Henrietta. Lady Nithsdale and her Family. 1939. 70086</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></BIOGRAPHY>